## Rationale and Usage

The current API does not provide an exception-free and simple approach to check if a collectible AssemblyLoadContext is alive or not (was unloaded).

```csharp
var myAssemblyLoadContext = new MyAssemblyLoadContext("MyAssemblyLoadContext", isCollectible: true);
myAssemblyLoadContext.Unload();
if(myAssemblyLoadContext.IsAlive) // would return false
{
   
}
```

## Proposed API
```csharp
namespace System.Runtime.Loader
{
    public partial class AssemblyLoadContext
    {
        // omitted the rest for brevity
        public bool IsAlive { get { throw null; } }
    }
}
```

## Open Questions

Internally there is a field of type `InternalState` that tracks the state of the `AssemblyLoadContext`. I couldn't find any resources about why the state isn't exposed on the public API surface - is there a good reason why?

## Pull Request

Awaiting review & approval before creating PR.

**Background**

`ConditionalWeakTable<TKey, TValue>` (CWT) contains a unique GC primitive as its building block called [DependentHandle](https://github.com/dotnet/coreclr/blob/master/src/System.Private.CoreLib/src/System/Runtime/CompilerServices/DependentHandle.cs) in source code or [ephemeron](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ephemeron) in general. It allows to keep a value alive as long as the key is alive. This functionality is not possible to implement outside the GC so it is a very valuable primitive, just like `GCHandle` and `WeakReference`.

However note that GCHandle is public, unlike DependentHandle, so users could implement their own WeakReference implementation if it wouldn't exist. Currently it is not possible to implement your own ConditionalWeakTable because the underlying GC primitive is not exposed.

Compared to WeakReference the desire to implement your own variation of CWT is much higher because it is a complex data structure. While theoretically you can use CWT itself as a building block for your other data structures, since CWT is a _collection_ you have to take a compromise:

* Create a single shared CWT with the associated lookup overhead and locking contention. If you cannot guarantee that your keys are unique you also have to make the `TValue` of the CWT a collection which adds another level of indirection and overhead. This is the recommended usage of CWT but its not suited for use cases which are more complex and would be better suited by having an individual reference as building block.
* Create a CWT for every site where you need a single reference, with the associated unnecessary indirection and overhead.
* Use reflection to access the native static methods on DependentHandle

The third option is currently by far the preferable one due to the much lower overhead when CWT doesn't provide a fit, though having to poke into runtime internals with reflection also feels wrong.

Note that there is a related but different request dotnet/coreclr#5508 to expose the `DependentHandle` directly. This proposal is not a duplicate, it adds a currently missing "safe" high level primitive in contrast to exposing the low level primitive of DependentHandle. If it were exposed you could implement the high level primitive yourself, but it would still be valuable to have in the framework, just as you have WeakReference and GCHandle living alongside.

**Motivation**

We often encounter situations where we want to make use of the GC liveness semantics of a DependentHandle without requiring the lookup semantics of a CWT, so being forced to go through a CWT adds a lot of unnecessary overhead to any implementation wanting to make use of this GC feature.

One particular important example are weak event managers. Historically these have been using WeakReference and regular polling of the table, but these implementations are inferior to a general purpose solution. What you want to say is _"keep this delegate alive as long as that other object is not GC'ed"_, a single DependentHandle would exactly represent this semantic. Note that you don't actually want to lookup events based on their keys, you have a list of DependentHandles as your weak event subscriptions. This is not possible to implement cleanly with the currently exposed ConditionalWeakTable API.

Similar scenarios keep happening over the years, where we just want a list of weak references being kept alive by something else, usually with interfaces instead of delegates, where we want to keep some sort of interface alive as long as something else is still alive.

**Proposal**

Implement and expose an analogue to `WeakReference<T>` wrapping the GC primitive used by CWT. I suggest the naming to be `ConditionalWeakReference<TKey, TValue>` because it accurately represents its semantics and relates in naming to both ConditionalWeakTable and WeakReference.

While you could also expose DependentHandle as analogue to GCHandle I currently have no practical use case for the low level access, all use cases I have encountered would be solvable by having a high level construct of a single conditional reference.

**Proposed API**

```C#
namespace System
{
    public sealed class ConditionalWeakReference<TKey, TValue>
        where TKey : class
        where TValue : class
    {
        public ConditionalWeakReference(TKey key, TValue value);
        ~ConditionalWeakReference();
        public bool TryGetKey(out TKey key);
        public bool TryGetValue(out TValue value);
        public bool TryGetKeyValue(out TKey key, out TValue value);
        public void SetKey(TKey key);
        public void SetValue(TValue value);
    }
}
```

- Making the class sealed is symmetric to `WeakReference<T>`
- `bool IsAlive { get; }` is not present on `WeakReference<T>` either so I omitted it. If you want to implement it, it would be equivalent to calling `TryGetKey` and discarding the key, like you can do with `WeakReference<T>.TryGetTarget`.
- Clearing the reference can be done by `SetKey(null)` which is the analogue to `WeakReference<T>.SetTarget(null)`
- Nullability annotations are missing, they are still new to me.

**Reference implementation**

<details><summary>expand</summary>

```C#
namespace System
{
    public sealed class ConditionalWeakReference<TKey, TValue>
        where TKey : class
        where TValue : class
    {
        private DependentHandle _handle;

        public ConditionalWeakReference(TKey key, TValue value)
        {
            if (key is null)
            {
                // if key is null then value also has to be null
                if (!(value is null))
                    throw new ArgumentNullException(nameof(key));
            }
            else
            {
                _handle = new DependentHandle(key, value);
            }
        }

        ~ConditionalWeakReference()
        {
            // ConditionalWeakTable does not free handles during AppDomain shutdown, so we don't do it either
            if (!Environment.HasShutdownStarted)
            {
                lock (this)
                {
                    _handle.Free();
                }
            }
        }

        public bool TryGetKey(out TKey key)
        {
            lock (this)
            {
                if (_handle.IsAllocated)
                {
                    var primary = _handle.GetPrimary();
                    if (primary != null)
                    {
                        key = (TKey)primary;
                        return true;
                    }
                }

                key = default;
                return false;
            }
        }

        public bool TryGetValue(out TValue value)
        {
            lock (this)
            {
                if (_handle.IsAllocated)
                {
                    var primary = _handle.GetPrimaryAndSecondary(out var secondary);
                    if (primary != null)
                    {
                        value = (TValue)secondary;
                        return true;
                    }
                }

                value = default;
                return false;
            }
        }

        public bool TryGetKeyValue(out TKey key, out TValue value)
        {
            lock (this)
            {
                if (_handle.IsAllocated)
                {
                    var primary = _handle.GetPrimaryAndSecondary(out var secondary);
                    if (primary != null)
                    {
                        key = (TKey)primary;
                        value = (TValue)secondary;
                        return true;
                    }
                }

                key = default;
                value = default;
                return false;
            }
        }

        public void SetKey(TKey key)
        {
            lock (this)
            {
                if (key is null)
                {
                    _handle.Free();
                }
                else
                {
                    if (!_handle.IsAllocated)
                        throw new InvalidOperationException();

                    _handle.SetPrimary(key);
                }
            }
        }

        public void SetValue(TValue value)
        {
            lock (this)
            {
                if (!_handle.IsAllocated)
                    throw new InvalidOperationException();

                _handle.SetSecondary(value);
            }
        }
    }
}
```
</details>

**Open questions**

- I'm not sure how much sense my reference implementation of `SetKey` and `SetValue` makes, they are primitives on DependentHandle so I included them in the API because they are required for being symmetric with WeakReference. If you feel like you don't want that an alternative would be making the class IDisposable instead.
- Should there be a `SetKeyValue(TKey, TValue)` to reinitialize the handle without reallocation of the ConditionalWeakReference?
- Should `SetKey(TKey)` with non-null key be allowed on an uninitialized handle and (instead of throwing) allocate a new handle with `TValue` set to null?
- The `lock (this)` in my reference implementation is not great. How is WeakReference<T> handling thread safety, does it just delegate to the runtime implementation? It should probably be analogous if possible, but this means the IsAllocated check must happen in DependentHandle or the runtime, not in the caller (invocation on IntPtr.Zero as handle should not throw)

This enables xUnit analyzer rule xUnit2002 which validates the expression being passed to `Assert.NotNull` is not a value type. The Roslyn code base had ~2,000 violations of this rule mostly due to passing `SyntaxToken` here. Presumably this is a historical artifact from the times when `SyntaxNode` was defined as a `class` instead of `struct`. 

The code was mechanically transformed in the following way:

``` csharp
// old
Assert.NotNull(token);
// new
Assert.NotEqual(default, token)
```

I did give some consideration to just removing all the uses of `Assert.NotNull` when the argument passed in was side effect free (mostly locals). Eventually I decided against this though because I didn't want to mix potentially deleting valuable code with a mechanical transformation. If we do want to remove the non-sense comparisons here we should take that as a separate change.

**Version Used**: master (31 Aug 2019) on SharpLab

**Steps to Reproduce**:
1.  Create a type with generic type parameters:
```cs
public readonly struct Box<T>
{
    public T Obj { get; }

    public Box(T obj)
    {
        this.Obj = obj;
    }
}
```
2. Attempt to use that type in an `is` expression with recursive pattern matching:
```cs
public static bool RecursiveIsBox<T>(object x)
{
    return x is Box<T> { Obj: T _ };
}
```
3. The following 5 errors are emitted:
```
error CS1525: Invalid expression term '{'
error CS1002: ; expected
error CS1002: ; expected
error CS0305: Using the generic type 'Box<T>' requires 1 type arguments
error CS0119: 'T' is a type, which is not valid in the given context
```

p.s.: SharpLab sample [here](https://sharplab.io/#v2:)

**Expected Behavior**:
The code is parsed and accepted and works in the same way as if the operations were done separately as in the following code:
```cs
public static bool IsBox<T>(object x)
{
    return x is Box<T> box && box.Obj is T _;
}
```

**Actual Behavior**:
The errors are emitted.

**Version Used**: Roslyn 2.7.0 or newer

**Steps to Reproduce**:

Run the following code:

```c#
using System;
using Microsoft.CodeAnalysis;
using Microsoft.CodeAnalysis.CSharp;

class Program
{
    static void Main()
    {
        string code = @"
struct S {}

static class Extensions
{
    static void M1(this ref S s) {}
    static void M2(ref this S s) {}
}";

        var tree = SyntaxFactory.ParseSyntaxTree(code, new CSharpParseOptions(LanguageVersion.CSharp7));

        var compilation = CSharpCompilation.Create("a.dll", options: new CSharpCompilationOptions(OutputKind.DynamicallyLinkedLibrary))
            .AddSyntaxTrees(tree)
            .AddReferences(MetadataReference.CreateFromFile(typeof(object).Assembly.Location));

        foreach (var diag in compilation.GetDiagnostics())
            Console.WriteLine(diag.ToString());
    }
}
```

**Expected Behavior**:

Both methods report an error saying that such code is not available in C# 7.0.

**Actual Behavior**:

Only `M2` reports an error:

> (7,20): error CS8107: Feature 'ref extension methods' is not available in C# 7.0. Please use language version 7.2 or greater.

I think this happens because when the ordering of modifiers on `ref` extension methods was relaxed in 2.7.0, a language version check wasn't added for the new syntax.

I think this isn't a serious problem and fixing it would be a breaking change, so this might not be worth fixing, but I thought it was worth reporting anyway.

This behavior was discovered in https://github.com/dotnet/docs/issues/13877.

**Version Used**: VS 16.2

**Steps to Reproduce**:

- Move caret to the first `i` and wait for it to be highlighted
- Move to next highlighted reference once (`Ctrl+Shift+Down`), wait 1 sec
- Move to next highlighted reference once (`Ctrl+Shift+Down`), wait 1 sec
- Move to next highlighted reference once (`Ctrl+Shift+Down`), only now it won't work

```C#
namespace ConsoleApp18
{
    class Program
    {
        static void Main(string[] args)
        {
            int i = 0;
            if (i == 1) { }
            i++;
            _ = i;
        }
    }
}
```

**Expected Behavior**:

The reference is still highlighted even if it's incrementing its value (`i++`) so you can move to the next reference again.

**Actual Behavior**:

The reference isn't highlighted anymore (it takes ~0.5 secs)

I think this is a regression.
